: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"St","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized spelling of French   St  .   Denis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Denis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Jacques, Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Serge, Yvan, Alphonse, Edouard, Francois, Gaetane.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Roberto, Angel, Francisco, Joaquin, Juan, Manuel, Miguel, Ramon, Rolando.","French, Walloon, Breton, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, Dutch, English, and Portuguese; Spanish and Galician (<b>Denís</b>): from the personal name <i>Denis</i>, Spanish and Galician <i>Denís</i>, from Latin <i>Dionysius</i> ‘(follower) of Dionysos’ (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dennee  .","Ukrainian and Rusyn: variant transliteration of   Denys  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Medard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Haitian (<b>Médard</b>): from the French personal name <i>Médard</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Madhard</i>, composed of the elements <i>mad</i> ‘respect’ and <i>hard</i> ‘hard’. This name was borne by a Christian saint, Saint Medardus (456–545), a Frankish bishop."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":5,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":14,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":49,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Peter de St Medard was born about 1210, in Thornhaugh, Northamptonshire, England as the son of Geoffery de St Medard. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs. Alice De St Medard."},"et":{"about 1210–":"umbes 1210–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1230–1280":"1230–1280","–Male":"Surnud","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1190":"1190","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","1230":"1230","about 1210":"umbes 1210","1280":"1280",